What is Linux File System?
Linux follows a tree structure starting from:
/
This is called the root directory.
Think of it like:
	/ → Main gate of building
	/home → User rooms 
	/etc → Configuration room
	/var → Logs and variable data
	/opt → Application installation
	/tmp → Temporary files


 Linux Special Symbols Notes
1. ^ (Caret symbol)
Use case 1 – Negation in regex / grep
Used to match start of line.

grep '^root'  /etc/passwd     ----------------- Shows lines starting with root
Grep -v '^root'  /etc/passwd     -----------------   Shows lines not starting with root
	• ^ outside brackets → start of line 
	• [^...] inside brackets → negation of characters (single char at a time)

Use case 2 – Negation inside brackets

ls [^a]*      ----------------------Shows files NOT starting with a

2. &> (Redirect both output and error)
Used to redirect stdout + stderr together

ls file1 file2 &> output.txt-------------------------Both normal output and error go to file
Example:

ls test1 test2 &> log.txt
If test2 not exist → error also saved in log.txt

3. 2> (Redirect error only)
2 = `stderr
> = redirect

ls file1 file2 2> error.txt ---------------Only error saved
Example:

ls test1 test2 2> err.txt
Output → screen
Error → err.txt

4. * (Wildcard – all)
Matches any number of characters
Use case 1
ls *----------------------All files
Use case 2
ls *.txt-------------------All txt files
Use case 3
rm file*---------------------Remove all files starting with file
